In [14]:
df_list = []

with open('tweet_json.txt', 'r', encoding='utf8') as f:
    for line in f:
        tweet_line = json.loads(line)
        df_list.append({'favorites': tweet_line['favorite_count'],
                       'retweets': tweet_line['retweet_count'],
                       'followers_count': tweet_line['user']['followers_count'],
                       'tweet_id': tweet_line['id']})
        
twitter_api = pd.DataFrame(df_list)
print(twitter_api)

The JSON file has 2337 rows and I have chosen 4 columns of interest to include in the DataFrame. Those are:

  • favorites: number of likes
  • followers_count: number of followers
  • retweets: number of times this Tweet has been retweeted
  • tweet_id: unique number to identify each Tweet

This file has 2075 rows and 12 columns, which are:

  • tweet_id: the final part of the URL, after status
  • jpg_URL: where the image is hosted
  • img_num: the image number that matches the most confident prediction, from 1 to 4
  • p1: the algorithm's first choice to predict the image in the tweet
  • p1_conf: how confident the algorithm is that the image is a breed of dog, in percentage
  • p1_dog: true or false, if the predicition is indeed a breed of dog
  • p2: algorithm's second most likely prediction
  • p2_conf: how confident the algorithm is that the image is a breed of dog, in percentage
  • p2_dog: true or false, if the predicition is indeed a breed of dog

2356 rows × 17 columns

This file has 2356 rows and 17 columns, as follows:

  • tweet_id: the unique number assigned to identify each Tweet
  • in_reply_to_status_id: if the referenced Tweet is a reply, this field will indicate the original Tweet's ID
  • in_reply_to_user_id: if the referenced Tweet is a reply, this field will indicate the original Tweet's author ID.
  • timestamp: date and time that the Tweet was published
  • source: app and hardware used to publish the Tweet
  • text: the text of the status update
  • retweeted_status_id/retweeted_status_user_id: if an original Tweet is shared by another user, this is called a retweet. These columns indicate whether the there has been a retweet and the user id of the user who retweeted.
  • expanded_urls: URL where the tweet can be found
  • rating_numerator: the top number of the fraction
  • rating_denominator: the bottom number of the fration
  • name: name of the dog
  • doggo/floofer/pupper/puppo: terms given to describe the age and appearance of the dog

Tidiness Issues¶

  • Merging the three dataframes, using the common tweet_id
  • Delete extraneous columns
  • The puppo/doggo/floofer/pupper terms should be in one column

We only want original ratings (no retweets) that have images. Though there are 5000+ tweets in the dataset, not all are dog ratings and some are retweets.

Quality Issues¶

  • Some tweets do not contain an image
  • Tweet_id should be a string, not integer
  • Retweets should be deleted
  • Some dog names are not actually names
  • Dog stages and img_num should be category type
  • rating_numerator should be float to accomodate decimals
  • Timestamp column should be converted to dateTime
  • Some of the numbers from rating_numerator and rating_denominator appear to be erroneous
  • Missing values in the puppo/doggo/floofer/pupper column

Quality Issue #9¶

Incorrect Numerators¶

A visual assessment showed that some ratings with decimals in the numerator were incorrectly exported into the rating_numerator column. For example, 9.5/10 was exported as 5.

In [65]:
decimals_text = []
decimals_index = []
with_decimals = []

for element, text in master['text'].iteritems():
    if bool(re.search('\d+\.\d+\/\d+', text)):
        decimals_text.append(text)
        decimals_index.append(element)
        with_decimals.append(re.search('\d+\.\d+', text).group())
